{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"03944e5d-557f-4bcf-86dd-bbd941b1cebc","content":"## What happened\n\nApple's security frameworks (`Security.framework` / `CryptoKit`) have **never** natively supported DSA. In earlier .NET versions, the runtime used an internal OpenSSL interop shim on macOS to fill the gap. In .NET 11, that shim was removed, so `DSA.Create()` now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS.\n\n## How to fix\n\n**Option 1 — BouncyCastle (recommended for verify-only)**\n\nUse the managed `BouncyCastle.Cryptography` NuGet package, which works on every platform:\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\nbool VerifyLegacyDsa(byte[] message, byte[] signature, DsaPublicKeyParameters pubKey)\n{\n    var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA1withDSA\");\n    verifier.Init(forSigning: false, pubKey);\n    verifier.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);\n    return verifier.VerifySignature(signature);\n}\n```\n\n**Option 2 — Explicit OpenSSL on macOS**\n\nInstall OpenSSL via Homebrew and use `DSAOpenSsl` directly (if still exposed):\n\n```csharp\nusing System.Security.Cryptography;\n\nDSA CreateDsa()\n{\n    if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())\n        return new DSAOpenSsl();   // requires libssl on PATH\n    return DSA.Create();\n}\n```\n\n**Option 3 (long-term) — Migrate off DSA entirely**\n\nDSA is a legacy algorithm with weak key sizes. If you control the signing side, re-sign with **ECDSA** or **Ed25519** and retire DSA.\n\n---\n\n**TL;DR:** Apple never supported DSA; .NET dropped its OpenSSL fallback on macOS. Use BouncyCastle for a managed cross-platform fix, and plan to migrate away from DSA.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3a3cba2a-e47d-4441-8038-9d55550ac64d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS when upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me think about what I know about 